Out of the six different countries of investigation (Algeria, Ghana, Indonesia, Malaysia, Nigeria and Palestine), 26 responses were acquired with an average of five participants. Although the number of respondents is limited due to an insufficient research scope under the BRI project, the number of responses is considered significant and directly reflects the outcome of the analysis as undergirded by the works of Gyamerah et al. (2021) and Butt et al. (2020) that mirror similar number of respondents. The selected participants have direct research experience and sufficient relevant knowledge of BRI projects in their respective countries. The participation of these countries is based on the history, current and future activities of the BRI, in line with the deep-rooted bilateral relations with China. The BRI projects in these countries can be broadly classified as road infrastructure, mining, energy and transport (see Table 4
                     ). Most participants shared relevant insights on the direction of BRI in promoting sustainable infrastructure and innovation development in their respective countries. Data from 26 interviews and 5 FGDs were processed, transcribed and transformed into a thematic analysis using the inductive method (Vaismoradi and Snelgrove, 2019). Respondents' statements were coded into the category’ Themes and Thematic Sections' using the software ATLAS.ti. The themes include; 1) the impact of the BRI on the sustainable development of industrial infrastructure (see Table 4), 2) the effect of BRI on environmental risks (see Table 5
                     ), and 3) spillover effect of BRI (see Fig. 1
                     ). Based on the responses, four out of the twelve questions asked produced similar answers (i.e., only two out of the four were relevant); these questions include Q3, Q4, Q10 and Q12. Responses for Q10 and Q12 were concisely excluded to avoid the repetition of answers. Consequently, 10 of the 12 variable questions were applicable and considered meaningful to answer this study's objectives. Hence, from Tables 4–5, eight questions (Q1 to Q6, Q8 and Q9) were utilised. However, the responses for Q7 and Q11 highlight the “Spillover effect analysis” in the discussion section.

This study found significant BRI developments in developing countries (like Algeria, Malaysia, Nigeria, Palestine, Ghana, and Indonesia) and each highlight a steady rise of sustainable infrastructure development in transport, energy, mining, water, and sanitation sectors. The progress of these developments with the SDGs agenda reflects the infrastructure development policies of the receiving nations (Seele et al., 2019; Ashraf et al., 2022). Some countries prioritise a sustainable development agenda, while others lack adequate sustainable development ambition. The BRIs have benefited more developing countries by creating several opportunities for trade openness. The import and export economic activities resulting from trade openness have significantly elevated the economic contribution of the BRI (Sun et al., 2019; Xiao et al., 2018; Chaturvedi, 2019). Among the six participating countries in this study, it is hard to deny that the BRI has positively influenced several key sectors of the economies as noted in the following interview participant's response. “China will overtake France as Algeria's top exporter of commodities to China, as the two countries' trade has grown recently. Algeria imports US$1.2 billion from China, which exports US$7.9 billion … " (I11, Male, Algeria) (See 

                        Table 4

                     ). Countries like Algeria and Palestine allow more BRI projects to facilitate the transaction of goods made in China. With the economic prospect of those countries, the intended BRI projects in the future will strengthen the trading partnership between the countries (Yuan et al., 2018; Sun et al., 2019).

Moreover, due to rapid industrialisation, more organisations are gradually digitalising their business activities (Nikulina, 2020). Consequentially, such optimistic developmental projection proves the relevance of the BRI projects since most infrastructural developments takes place with relevant technology. For instance, several businesses in Malaysia are accepting digital technology as the new normal, and a part of the BRI projects is influencing the use of digital technology for innovation (through research and training), especially in the railway infrastructure development sector (Jiang and Hui, 2021; Sharma and Kundu, 2016; Qi et al., 2019). A participant argued that “Several BRI projects promote training for local managers, engineers, technicians and operators about new smart technology to improve firm production system” (I8, Male, Malaysia) (See 

                        Table 4

                     ). Unlike Malaysia, other economies like Singapore and Thailand are nurturing the source of innovation through better integration and technology optimisation through BRI projects (Jiang and Hui, 2021).

The green urbanisation program, progressing steadily in the form of forest cities in countries like Malaysia, significantly reflects green development measures for BRI projects (Rauf et al., 2020). According to Amighini (2018), the initiatives also exhibit the Chinese government's ambition to promote the sustainable development agenda in other BRI projects. This study revealed some conclusions on the ‘green development agenda’ as “Major Chinese investments and construction contracts in peninsular Malaysia include multiple airports, ports, expressway, forest city and the Malaysia-China Kuantan Industrial Park … " (I10, Male, Malaysia) (See 

                        Table 4

                     ). Although there is still doubt about how far the BRI projects can go as far as green environmental development is concerned, the emphasis on green development projects in some areas in Southeast Asia is near reality (Muhammad et al., 2020; Wei et al., 2021).

This study reveals that with the introduction of BRI, policies encourage investment in large-scale renewable energy generation in biogas, solar, hydro and biomass. The BRI projects in the renewable energy sector are exponentially increasing due to the high demand for renewable energy (Kumar 2007). A participant also stated that "Algeria's government and China BRI projects are looking to expand solar energy production making the energy sector as one of the major sectors …." (I11 Male, Algeria) (See 

                        Table 4

                     ). Renewable energy development is crucial to building a sustainable environment and economy (Zeng et al., 2020; Kumar 2007). In Indonesia, some BRI projects emphasise the effort to generate hydroelectricity and eventually promote the sustainable development agenda (Feng et al., 2019; Jiang et al., 2021). The awareness to explore renewable energy sources such as solar, water and wind is rapidly forming the key foundation to building sustainable renewable energy (Arminen and Menegaki, 2019). This study reveals that over 75% of the BRI, including roads, ports, and railways, account for transport infrastructure projects. The project entails the development of basic infrastructure facilities that the country does not have (Garlick, 2017). According to Table 4, a participant emphasised that, “Infrastructure project such rail route, gas line, properties, and new town. It covers the whole country.” “There are few mega projects involved BRI in Malaysia. Highways and railways are the two main projects involved” (FGD1, P5) (See 

                        Table 4

                     ). Although the projects cover transport infrastructure development, it also entails several diverse economic development sectors (Menhas et al., 2019).

This study found few environmental risks of BRI projects in lower-middle-income countries like Ghana, Nigeria, and others. Unlike the upper-middle-income countries, BRI projects are guided by resilient infrastructure development and environmental policies. Lower-middle income and poor nations struggle to deal with the negative impact of BRI projects due to either lack of rugged environmental protection policies or the inability to enforce existing policies (Cai et al., 2018; Ahmad et al., 2018). To industrial pollution, several countries worldwide, especially developing countries in Asia, Latin America and Africa, are struggling with waste management. All participating countries in this study have highlighted similar struggles as captured in the following participants' statements. “Environmental issues like air pollution affect air quality. The BRI projects will produce more sulphur oxide and chlorofluorocarbon emissions” (I6 Female, Indonesia). “As a result of habitat fragmentation and degradation caused by the BRI, biodiversity may be lost, and greenhouse gas emissions may rise as a result of the construction and maintenance of transportation infrastructure” (FGD1, P4) (see 

                        Table 5

                     ). The damaging effect of environmental risks on human health is deadly. People suffer from all kinds of health issues, such as skin and respiratory diseases, lung cancer etc., from excessive carbon emission (Zeng and Wang, 2022; Lee et al., 2021; World Health Organization, 2020). The outcome of the BRI projects is significant for economic growth and development. However, the continued development without proper environmental protection measures will soon lead to devastating consequences (Yuan et al., 2018; Wan et al., 2019).

Depleting natural resources to expand development is a long-term struggle for many resource-rich countries (Zhao et al., 2021). Countries such as Algeria, rich in oil and gas, Ghana in Gold and bauxite, and Nigeria in oil, gas and labour, have all shown to have lapses when dealing with activities like mining. With such an inevitable struggle, more than 70% of the world's natural resources are currently being exploited and depleted in the quest for power domination (Zhao et al., 2021; Sarker et al., 2018). This study found that a country like Ghana is currently battling with resource depletion where the government continue approving loan agreement to expand Chinese road infrastructure development in return for bauxite extraction. A participant argued that “Majority of BRI projects in the mining sectors in Ghana focus on resources extractions without any effort to protect the natural forest …." (I9, Male, Ghana) (See 

                        Table 5

                     ). However, many citizens believe Ghana's-Chinese infrastructure development initiatives are a progressive step towards economic development. A large number of the Ghanian citizens have lost faith in the effort to protect the land and resources for the next generation (Venkateswaran, 2020).

Mass deforestation activities to enable the BRI projects to commerce without adequate measures to protect the ecosystem is troubling, and need urgent environmental actions from the global regulatory bodies. Most importantly, it controls climate change effects (GSIA, 2019; Anwar et al., 2021; Yang et al., 2019). Based on discussions from the focused groups, there is currently little or no effort to protect the forestry and ecosystem. Due to that, the world is struggling with climate change effects like flooding, high weather temperature and others. Participants espoused that “BRI projects involve deforestation, and the risk of deforestation through the establishment of forest cities will pose serious short-term environmental risks …. In some way, the BRI projects in road, ports, rail infrastructure development lead to climate change since ecosystems have been destroyed” (FGD3, P4) (see 

                        Table 5

                     ). Even though all BRI projects are meant to comply with sustainable development initiatives, there are still lapses in developing environmental protection policies and law enforcement (EIB 2018; Lee et al., 2021).
